        transition: none !important;
    }
    .whatsapp-button:hover,
    .whatsapp-button:active {
        transform: none;
        animation: none;
    }
}

thoughts.content:
To fix the issue, update `.hero .hero-media img` with this CSS code:

```css
.hero .hero-media img { 
  height: 100% !important; 
  object-fit: cover; 
  object-position: center; 
}
```

This will override the inline `height: auto`. Add this after your existing `.hero` rules for proper override. Inline styles are more specific, so `!important` ensures the CSS works.

For the `index.html` reference, the inline style defines `height: auto` (turn0file0), and the CSS file with this rule modifies it (turn0file1).

parts:
Add one override so your `<img>` ignores its inline `height:auto` and always covers the hero’s computed height:

```css
/* Force hero image to fill the hero section’s height on all screens */
.hero .hero-media img{
  height: 100% !important;   /* beats inline height:auto */
  width: 100%;               /* already true; kept for clarity */
  object-fit: cover;         /* crop to cover */
  object-position: center;
}
```

Place that after the existing `.hero .hero-media img` rule in `tuition-css-1.0.1-phase6.css`. This doesn’t touch any padding or margins; it only fixes the image box sizing. fileciteturn0file1

Why it’s needed: the hero `<img>` in your HTML has an inline style `height:auto`, which overrides the stylesheet and prevents the image from filling the section’s height. The `!important` restores the intended behavior. fileciteturn0file0
